{"questionId":"9369","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Adam sets out for a hike from his camp at point A. He hikes at an average speed of 4.2 km/h&nbsp;for 45 minutes, on a bearing of 035° from the camp, until he stops for a break at point B.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/29cd66593bc90b834b712953163ad368c89e6c1c.png\"></p>\n<p>Adam leaves point B on a bearing of 114° and continues to hike for a distance of 4.6‌ km until&nbsp;he reaches point C.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/796c322c088c456746e923fb6249590a8953f47c.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Show that <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{A}}\\mathop {\\text{B}}\\limits^ \\wedge&nbsp; {\\text{C}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>A</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mover>\n    <mrow>\n      <mtext>B</mtext>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>∧</mo>\n  </mover>\n  <mo>⁡</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>C</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span> is 101°.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>66° or (180&nbsp;− 114)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>35 + 66&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{A}}\\mathop {\\text{B}}\\limits^ \\wedge&nbsp; {\\text{C}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>A</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mover>\n    <mrow>\n      <mtext>B</mtext>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>∧</mo>\n  </mover>\n  <mo>⁡</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>C</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;= 101°&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9369","referenceCode":"SPM.2.SL.TZ0.7b.i","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Show that A B ∧ ⁡ C is 101°.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.2—2d and 3d trig, sine rule, cosine rule, area","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.3—Applications: angles of elevation and depression, bearings"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}